An activity (an Observation or an Actuation) can be ordered by a User, in which case the device performing the activity is responsible for carrying it out, but the User is responsible for making the decision to do so. Ordering an activity may involve more than making a decision, i.e. actually using the device to perform an Actuation, or an Observation by handling the device physically, or controlling it remotely.

An anonymous device will not have a User that orderd its activity, itself being responsible for making the decision to perform it.

skosExamples.annotation:
A port operator that moves a port crane orders an actuation that is then made by the crane device.

A doctor that uses a smart thermometer to measure a patients temperature orders the temperature observation carried out by the thermometer.

A truck driver that sets the preferred fuel usage in a smart car orders it to make an actuation, making the smart truck controller device change the state of the smart truck and recalculate route data (e.g. estimated time of arrival).

comments.annotation: An Actuation carries out an (Actuation) Procedure to change the state of the world using an Actuator.

skosExamples.annotation: The activity of automatically closing a window if the temperature in a room drops below 20 degree Celsius. The activity is the Actuation and the device that closes the window is the Actuator. The Procedure is the rule, plan, or specification that defines the conditions that triggers the Actuation, here a drop in temperature.

comments.annotation: Physical samples are sometimes known as 'specimens'.

Samples are artifacts of an observational strategy, and have no significant function outside of their role in the observation process. The characteristics of the samples themselves are of little interest, except perhaps to the manager of a sampling campaign.

A Sample is intended to sample some FatureOfInterest, so there is an expectation of at least one isSampleOf property. However, in some cases the identity, and even the exact type, of the sampled feature may not be known when observations are made using the sampling features.
Feature which is intended to be representative of a FeatureOfInterest on which Observations may be made.
A Sample is the result from an act of Sampling.

skosExamples.annotation: A 'station' is essentially an identifiable locality where a sensor system or Procedure may be deployed and an observation made. In the context of the observation model, it connotes the 'world in the vicinity of the station', so the observed properties relate to the physical medium at the station, and not to any physical artifact such as a mooring, buoy, benchmark, monument, well, etc.

A statistical sample is often designed to be characteristic of an entire population, so that observations can be made regarding the sample that provide a good estimate of the properties of the population.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Feature which is intended to be representative of a FeatureOfInterest on which Observations may be made.

annotations.annotation: A transient sample, such as a ships-track or flight-line, might be identified and described, but is unlikely to be revisited exactly.

comments.annotation: A device that is used by, or implements, a Sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.

skosExamples.annotation: A ball mill, diamond drill, hammer, hypodermic syringe and needle, image Sensor or a soil auger can all act as sampling devices (i.e., be Samplers). However, sometimes the distinction between the Sampler and the Sensor is not evident, as they are packaged as a unit. A Sampler need not be a physical device.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A device that is used by, or implements, a Sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.

skosDefinitions.annotation: An actuatable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.

skosExamples.annotation: The value 20 as the height of a certain tree together with the unit, e.g., Meter.

skosDefinitions.annotation: The Result of an Observation, Actuation, or act of Sampling. To store an observation's simple result value one can use the hasSimpleResult property.

comments.annotation: A relation between an Observation and the entity whose quality was observed, or between an Actuation and the entity whose property was modified, or between an act of Sampling and the entity that was sampled.

skosExamples.annotation: For example, in an Observation of the weight of a person, the FeatureOfInterest is the person and the property is its weight.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A relation between an Observation and the entity whose quality was observed, or between an Actuation and the entity whose property was modified, or between an act of Sampling and the entity that was sampled.

comments.annotation: Relation between a Sensor and an Observation made by the Sensor.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation between a Sensor and an Observation made by the Sensor.

comments.annotation: A workflow, protocol, plan, algorithm, or computational method specifying how to make an Observation, create a Sample, or make a change to the state of the world (via an Actuator). A Procedure is re-usable, and might be involved in many Observations, Samplings, or Actuations. It explains the steps to be carried out to arrive at reproducible results.

skosExamples.annotation: The measured wind speed differs depending on the height of the sensor above the surface, e.g., due to friction. Consequently, procedures for measuring wind speed define a standard height for anemometers above ground, typically 10m for meteorological measures and 2m in Agrometeorology. This definition of height, sensor placement, and so forth are defined by the Procedure.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A workflow, protocol, plan, algorithm, or computational method specifying how to make an Observation, create a Sample, or make a change to the state of the world (via an Actuator). A Procedure is re-usable, and might be involved in many Observations, Samplings, or Actuations. It explains the steps to be carried out to arrive at reproducible results.

annotations.annotation: Many observations may be created via the same Procedure, the same way as many tables are assembled using the same instructions (as information objects, not their concrete realization).

comments.annotation: A device that is used by, or implements, an (Actuation) Procedure that changes the state of the world.

skosExamples.annotation: A window actuator for automatic window control, i.e., opening or closing the window.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A device that is used by, or implements, an (Actuation) Procedure that changes the state of the world.

comments.annotation: Relation between a Platform and a Sensor, Actuator, Sampler, or Platform, hosted or mounted on it.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation between a Platform and a Sensor, Actuator, Sampler, or Platform, hosted or mounted on it.

comments.annotation: Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to a Sensor to describe what made the Observation and how; links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that property was associated with.

skosExamples.annotation: The activity of estimating the intensity of an Earthquake using the Mercalli intensity scale is an Observation as is measuring the moment magnitude, i.e., the energy released by said earthquake.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Act of carrying out an (Observation) Procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a FeatureOfInterest. Links to a Sensor to describe what made the Observation and how; links to an ObservableProperty to describe what the result is an estimate of, and to a FeatureOfInterest to detail what that property was associated with.

comments.annotation: The result time is the instant of time when the Observation, Actuation or Sampling activity was completed.

skosDefinitions.annotation: The result time is the instant of time when the Observation, Actuation or Sampling activity was completed.

comments.annotation: Relation linking an Actuation to the Actuator that made that Actuation.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation linking an Actuation to the Actuator that made that Actuation.

comments.annotation: A relation between a FeatureOfInterest and an Observation about it, an Actuation acting on it, or an act of Sampling that sampled it.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A relation between a FeatureOfInterest and an Observation about it, an Actuation acting on it, or an act of Sampling that sampled it.

comments.annotation: Relation between a FeatureOfInterest and the Sample used to represent it.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation between a FeatureOfInterest and the Sample used to represent it.

comments.annotation: A Platform is an entity that hosts other entities, particularly Sensors, Actuators, Samplers, and other Platforms.

skosExamples.annotation: A post, buoy, vehicle, ship, aircraft, satellite, cell-phone, human or animal may act as platforms for (technical or biological) sensors or actuators.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A Platform is an entity that hosts other entities, particularly Sensors, Actuators, Samplers, and other Platforms.

comments.annotation: Device, agent (including humans), or software (simulation) involved in, or implementing, a Procedure. Sensors respond to a stimulus, e.g., a change in the environment, or input data composed from the results of prior Observations, and generate a Result. Sensors can be hosted by Platforms.

skosExamples.annotation: Accelerometers, gyroscopes, barometers, magnetometers, and so forth are Sensors that are typically mounted on a modern smart phone (which acts as Platform). Other examples of sensors include the human eyes.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Device, agent (including humans), or software (simulation) involved in, or implementing, a (Sensing) Procedure. Sensors respond to a stimulus, e.g., a change in the environment, or input data composed from the results of prior Observations, and generate a Result. Sensors can be hosted by Platforms.

comments.annotation: Relation linking an Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling and a Result or Sample.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation linking an Observation or Actuation or act of Sampling and a Result or Sample.

comments.annotation: Relation between an ActuatableProperty of a FeatureOfInterest and an Actuation changing its state.

skosExamples.annotation: In the activity (Actuation) of automatically closing a window if the temperature in a room drops below 20 degrees Celsius, the property on which the Actuator acts upon is the state of the window as it changes from being open to being closed.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation between an ActuatableProperty of a FeatureOfInterest and an Actuation changing its state.

comments.annotation: The thing whose property is being estimated or calculated in the course of an Observation to arrive at a Result or whose property is being manipulated by an Actuator, or which is being sampled or transformed in an act of Sampling.

skosExamples.annotation: When measuring the height of a tree, the height is the observed ObservableProperty, 20m may be the Result of the Observation, and the tree is the FeatureOfInterest. A window is a FeatureOfInterest for an automatic window control Actuator.

skosDefinitions.annotation: The thing whose property is being estimated or calculated in the course of an Observation to arrive at a Result or whose property is being manipulated by an Actuator, or which is being sampled or transformed in an act of Sampling.

comments.annotation: Relation linking an act of Sampling to the Sampler (sampling device or entity) that made it.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation linking an act of Sampling to the Sampler (sampling device or entity) that made it.

comments.annotation: An act of Sampling carries out a sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.

skosExamples.annotation: Taking a diamond-drill core from a rock outcrop.
Selecting a subset of a population.
Splitting a piece of drill-core to create two new samples.
Crushing a rock sample in a ball mill.
Registering an image of the landscape.
Dividing a field site into quadrants.
Digging a pit through a soil sequence.
Drawing blood from a patient.
Sieving a powder to separate the subset finer than 100-mesh.
Drilling an observation well.
Establishing a station for environmental monitoring.

skosDefinitions.annotation: An act of Sampling carries out a sampling Procedure to create or transform one or more samples.

comments.annotation: Relation between an Actuation and the property of a FeatureOfInterest it is acting upon.

skosExamples.annotation: In the activity (Actuation) of automatically closing a window if the temperature in a room drops below 20 degrees Celsius, the property on which the Actuator acts upon is the state of the window as it changes from being open to being closed.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation between an Actuation and the property of a FeatureOfInterest it is acting upon.

comments.annotation: Relation between an Actuator and the Actuation it has made.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation between an Actuator and the Actuation it has made.

comments.annotation: An observable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.

skosExamples.annotation: The height of a tree, the depth of a water body, or the temperature of a surface are examples of observable properties, while the value of a classic car is not (directly) observable but asserted.

skosDefinitions.annotation: An observable quality (property, characteristic) of a FeatureOfInterest.

comments.annotation: Relation between a Platform and a Deployment, meaning that the deployedSystems of the Deployment are hosted on the Platform.

skosExamples.annotation: For example, a relation between a buoy and a deployment of several Sensors.

skosDefinitions.annotation: Relation between a Platform and a Deployment, meaning that the deployedSystems of the Deployment are hosted on the Platform.

skosExamples.annotation: For example, from a Sensor to the properties it can observe; from an Actuator to the properties it can act on; from a Deployment to the properties it was installed to observe or act on; from a SystemCapability to the Property the capability is described for.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A relation between some aspect of an entity and a Property.

entities.name: Property

comments.annotation: A quality of an entity. An aspect of an entity that is intrinsic to and cannot exist without the entity.

skosDefinitions.annotation: A quality of an entity. An aspect of an entity that is intrinsic to and cannot exist without the entity.

entities.Restrictions: ssn:isPropertyOf only sosa:FeatureOfInterest

entities.name: Result
entities.Restrictions: sosa:isResultOf min 1 owl:Thing

comments.annotation: Relation between a Procedure (an algorithm, procedure or method) and an entity that implements that Procedure in some executable way.

skosExamples.annotation: For example, the relationship between a scientific measuring Procedure and a sensor that senses via that Procedure.

entities.name: Stimulus

comments.annotation: An event in the real world that 'triggers' the Sensor. The properties associated to the Stimulus may be different to the eventual observed ObservableProperty. It is the event, not the object, that triggers the Sensor.

skosDefinitions.annotation: An event in the real world that 'triggers' the Sensor. The properties associated to the Stimulus may be different to the eventual observed ObservableProperty. It is the event, not the object, that triggers the Sensor.

comments.annotation: Describes the Deployment of one or more Systems for a particular purpose. Deployment may be done on a Platform.

skosExamples.annotation: For example, a temperature Sensor deployed on a wall, or a whole network of Sensors deployed for an Observation campaign.
